Lab 4: ggplot2 and Visualization Principles

In May 2020, the Georgia Department of Public Health posted the following plot to illustrate the number of confirmed COVID-19 cases in their hardest-hit counties over a two-week period.

The plot was heavily criticized by the statistical community and several media outlets for its deceptive portrayal of COVID-19 trends in Georgia. Whether the end result was due to malicious intent or simply poor judgment, it is incredibly irresponsible to publish data visualizations that obscure and distort the truth.

In this lab, we will pretend that we are data scientists tasked with the job of making better COVID-19 visualizations. This will also give us an opportunity to practice making more aesthetically pleasing plots using the ggplot2 package. For the remainder of the course, you will be expected to use ggplot2 any time you create a plot.

We will use the New York Times COVID-19 data to get county-level information for Georgia. The numbers look slightly different from the ones reported by the Georgia DPH, but thats okay for our purposes. The code below reads in the the data through September 30, 2020 that is saved in the us-counties.csv file in the lab folder. If you would like to pull the most up-to-date version of the data, you can replace read_csv("us-counties.csv") with read_csv("https://raw.githubusercontent.com/nytimes/covid-19-data/master/us-counties.csv") in the code below.

library(readr)
library(dplyr)
library(ggplot2)
library(gridExtra)

# Replace "us-counties.csv" with 
# "https://raw.githubusercontent.com/nytimes/covid-19-data/master/us-counties.csv"
# to pull most up-to-date version from Github
us_counties = read_csv("us-counties.csv")

This lab (particularly questions 10 and 11) borrows ideas and code from Peter Elliss blog post.

  1. Create a new data frame called georgia_counties that only contains the data from Georgia. Add a new variable called new_cases that stores the number of new confirmed cases for each day at the county level. Hint: the lag function returns the previous values in a vector.

Solution:

Note that group_by(county) ensures that the new cases are calculated within each county, and arrange(date) sorts the dates in ascending order, to make sure that that the lags are calculated correctly.

georgia_counties = us_counties %>%
  filter(state == "Georgia") %>%
  group_by(county) %>%
  arrange(date) %>%
  mutate(new_cases = cases - lag(cases)) %>% 
  ungroup()
  1. Today is May 9th, 2020. You want to get a sense of todays distribution of the total number of confirmed cases in each county in Georgia. Make three histograms, one with 10 black bins, one with 30 red bins, and one with 50 blue bins. Include nice axis labels and titles. Use the grid.arrange function from the gridExtra package to place the three plots next to each other.

Solution:

First, we can create a new data frame with just the data from May 9, 2020.

georgia_counties_may9 =  georgia_counties %>% 
  filter(date == as.Date("2020-05-09"))

Then, we want to create and save the three histograms. The bins argument controls the number of bins and the fill argument determines what color to fill them in. We can also specify better titles using ggtitle, xlab, and ylab.

p1 = georgia_counties_may9 %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = cases)) + geom_histogram(bins = 10, fill = "black") + 
  ggtitle("10 bins") + xlab("Cases") + ylab("")
p2 = georgia_counties_may9 %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = cases)) + geom_histogram(bins = 30, fill = "red") + 
  ggtitle("30 bins") + xlab("Cases") + ylab("")
p3 = georgia_counties_may9 %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = cases)) + geom_histogram(bins = 50, fill = "blue") + 
  ggtitle("50 bins") + xlab("Cases") + ylab("")

Finally, we can use grid.arrange to put the saved histograms side-by-side.

grid.arrange(p1, p2, p3, ncol = 3)

  1. A single day doesnt tell the whole story, so you decide to look at the data from the past two weeks, April 26 to May 9, 2020. Boxplots can be easier to interpret than histograms when you are comparing the distributions of multiple groups. Draw boxplots of the total number of confirmed cases in each county by date. Try this with and without a log (base 10) transformation.

Solution:

Make a data frame that stores only the data from April 26 to May 9, 2020.

georgia_counties_apr26_may9 = georgia_counties %>% 
  filter(date >= as.Date("2020-04-26")) %>%
  filter(date <= as.Date("2020-05-09"))

Here are the boxplots without transforming the data.

georgia_counties_apr26_may9 %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = date, y = cases, group = date)) + 
  geom_boxplot() + 
  xlab("Date") + ylab("Cases")

Here are the boxplots after applying a log transform.

georgia_counties_apr26_may9 %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = date, y = cases, group = date)) + 
  geom_boxplot() + 
  xlab("Date") + ylab("Cases (log scale)") + 
  scale_y_log10()

  1. From your plots in Questions 2 and 3, it is clear that there are some counties with a lot of cases! It might be useful to study them more closely. Identify the five most impacted counties, which we will take to be the counties with the highest case totals on May 9, 2020.

Solution:

The slice_max function is a nifty way to pull out the five rows of georgia_counties_may9 with the most cases.

georgia5_names = georgia_counties_may9 %>%
  slice_max(order_by = cases, n=5) %>%
  pull(county) %>% sort()

georgia5_names
## [1] "Cobb"     "DeKalb"   "Fulton"   "Gwinnett" "Hall"
  1. We are not going to spend time bending over backwards to try to re-create the very bad barplot from the Georgia DPH, but Peter Ellis explains how to do it in his blog post. Instead, make an improved clustered barplot of the new cases reported in the 5 most impacted counties between April 26 and May 9. Be sure to order the dates chronologically on the x-axis and maintain the order of the counties within each days cluster of bars. Does your impression of the COVID-19 situation in Georgia change?

Solution:

Lets subset the data to only include observations from the top five counties during the last two weeks.

georgia5_apr26_may9 = georgia_counties %>% 
  filter(county %in% georgia5_names) %>%
  filter(date >= as.Date("2020-04-26")) %>%
  filter(date <= as.Date("2020-05-09"))

Setting position = position_dodge() and specifying the barplot group to be county gets us the clusters. By default, ggplot2 orders the dates chronologically and maintains the order of the counties in the clusters. Note that we can specify the legend title to be County (or anything else we want) using scale_fill_discrete(name = "County").

georgia5_apr26_may9 %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = date, weight = new_cases, fill = county)) +
  geom_bar(position = position_dodge(), aes(group = county)) + 
  xlab("Date") + ylab("New Cases") + scale_fill_discrete(name = "County")

  1. While much improved, the clustered barplot still makes it difficult to compare trends over time in the five counties. Present the data as a line plot with the date on the x-axis, the number of new cases on the y-axis, and each county plotted as a separate line.

Solution:

georgia5_apr26_may9 %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = date, y = new_cases, color = county)) +
  geom_line() + 
  xlab("Date") + ylab("New Cases") + scale_color_discrete(name = "County")

  1. Several months have passed and it is now September 30, 2020 (or whatever the most recent date is in your data). Update your plot from Question 6 so that it includes all of the data from the start of the pandemic until today.

Solution:

georgia5_all = georgia_counties %>% 
  filter(county %in% georgia5_names)

ggplot(georgia5_all, aes(x = date, y = new_cases, color = county)) +
  geom_line() + 
  xlab("Date") + ylab("New Cases") + scale_color_discrete(name = "County")

  1. Unfortunately, because you have so much more data now, it is difficult to see the separate lines in your plot from Question 7 and draw conclusions. Try plotting all of the lines in gray and adding a black line representing the average number of new cases across the five counties.

Solution:

First, we create a data frame that stores the average number of new cases on each day.

georgia5_all_avg = georgia5_all %>%
  group_by(date) %>%
  summarize(mean_new_cases = mean(new_cases))
## `summarise()` ungrouping output (override with `.groups` argument)

Setting aes(group = county) in the first geom_line call ensures that a different gray line is plotted for each county. georgia5_all_avg does not have a county variable/grouping, which is why we didnt want to pass group = county into the aes in the top call to ggplot. We can add the black average line by passing georgia5_all_avg into another call to geom_line.

ggplot(georgia5_all, aes(x = date, y = new_cases)) +
  geom_line(color = "gray", aes(group = county)) +
  geom_line(data = georgia5_all_avg, aes(x = date, y = mean_new_cases)) +
  xlab("Date") + ylab("New Cases")
## Warning: Removed 5 row(s) containing missing values (geom_path).
## Warning: Removed 1 row(s) containing missing values (geom_path).

  1. The line plot from Question 8 is a lot easier on the eyes, but it doesnt resolve the issue that we are unable to visually compare the five counties. Try making a scatterplot of the data, with slightly transparent points colored by county. Then, add a loess line for each county that smooths over local points (advanced). This will help you track the general trends in each county, instead of being distracted by all of the day-to-day variability.

Solution:

The alpha argument controls the transparency of the points, with 1 being completely opaque and 0 being completely transparent. We can add loess lines using the geom_smooth function with method set to "loess". se = FALSE prevents the function from plotting the standard errors, which may be useful for other scenarios but would over-complicate an already busy plot here. The span argument controls the amount of smoothing.

ggplot(georgia5_all, aes(x = date, y = new_cases, color = county)) +
  geom_point(alpha = 0.5) +
  geom_smooth(se = FALSE, span = 0.5, method = "loess") + 
  xlab("Date") + ylab("New Cases") + scale_color_discrete(name = "County")
## `geom_smooth()` using formula 'y ~ x'
## Warning: Removed 5 rows containing non-finite values (stat_smooth).
## Warning: Removed 5 rows containing missing values (geom_point).

  1. Instead of putting all of the points and loess lines in a single plot, make a multi-panel plot with a panel for each county using facet_wrap.

Solution:

Note that theme(legend.position = "none") removes the legend.

ggplot(georgia5_all, aes(x = date, y = new_cases, color = county)) +
  geom_point(alpha = 0.5) +
  geom_smooth(se = FALSE, span = 0.5, method = "loess") + 
  xlab("Date") + ylab("New Cases")  +
  facet_wrap(~county) +
  theme(legend.position = "none")

  1. (Optional, advanced) Re-create your plot from Question 5 so that the colors and text match the very bad barplot published by the Georgia DPH.

Solution:

Much of the code for the colors and themes was adapted from Peter Elliss blog post, with some modifications.

The fill_palette vector stores the hex color codes for filling the bars, and the stroke_palette vector stores the hex color codes for outlining the bars (these are slightly lighter).

fill_palette = c(
  "Cobb" = "#5954b0",
  "DeKalb" = "#238a8f",
  "Fulton" = "#98863c",
  "Gwinnett" = "#965b31",
  "Hall" = "#2460ac"
)

stroke_palette = c(
  "Cobb" = "#827cf8",
  "DeKalb" = "#42d1e1",
  "Fulton" = "#e5cd63",
  "Gwinnett" = "#e28f4d",
  "Hall" = "#3da2f2"
)

The following step is pretty advanced and truly optional, so dont worry if it goes over your head. Here, we are creating and saving a ggplot theme that is based on the minimal theme_minimal theme and adds customization on top of it. A lot of this is specifying colors for different plot elements, like the background, axes, and text. To summarize:

  • panel.grid = element_blank() gets rid of the grid lines
  • The element_text function is used to specify various components for displaying text, including color for color, size for font size in pts, face for font face (like bold or italic), and hjust for horizontal justification. element_rect and element_line are the analgous functions for borders/backgrounds and lines, with slightly different argument options.
  • legend.position = "top" moves the legend to the top of the plot, instead of the default right of the plot.
  • legend.key.size = unit(0.5, units = "line") sets the size of the boxes for the fill colors in the legend to be smaller.

Please see the help page for theme to get a detailed description of all of the options.

my_theme = theme_minimal() +
  theme(panel.background = element_rect(fill = "#0f3051", color = NA),
        panel.grid = element_blank(),
        plot.background = element_rect(fill = "#0f3051"),
        text = element_text(color = "grey70"),
        axis.text = element_text(color = "grey70"),
        axis.line = element_line(color = "grey90"),
        strip.text = element_text(color = "grey80"),
        plot.title = element_text(size = 10, face = "bold", color = "white"), 
        plot.subtitle = element_text(size = 8, color = "#c0e5e5"), 
        legend.title = element_text(size = 6, face = "bold", 
                                    color="white", hjust = 0.5), 
        legend.text = element_text(size = 6), 
        legend.position = "top", 
        legend.key.size = unit(0.5, units = "line"))

The title and subtitle are pretty long, so we can store them ahead of time as strings.

title = "Top 5 Counties with the Greatest Number of Confirmed COVID-19 Cases"

subtitle = "The chart below represents the most impacted counties over the past 15 days and the number of cases over time. The table below \n also represents the number of deaths and hospitalizations in each of those impacted counties."

Putting it all together, we get a plot that is stylistically almost identical to the original bad barplot. Some final notes:

  • guides(color = guide_legend(title.position = "top")) ensures that the legend title is at the top of the legend, instead of defaulting to the side.
  • scale_x_date gives finer control for date axes. In particular, we passed in a custom set of break points running from April 26, 2020 to May 9, 2020 in one-day intervals. date_labels = "%d%b%Y" specifies that the labels should be displayed in ddmmyyyy format with no spaces in between. Finally, guide = guide_axis(n.dodge = 2) shifts the x-axis tick mark labels to alternate between two rows.
ggplot(georgia5_apr26_may9, aes(x = date, weight = new_cases, 
                          fill = county, color = county)) +
  geom_bar(position = position_dodge(), aes(group = county)) + 
  labs(title = title,  subtitle = subtitle, x = "", y = "") + 
  guides(color = guide_legend(title.position = "top")) + 
  scale_color_manual(name = "County", values = stroke_palette) +
  scale_fill_manual(name = "County", values = fill_palette) +
  scale_x_date(breaks = seq(as.Date("2020-04-26"), 
                            as.Date("2020-05-09"), by="1 day"), 
               date_labels = "%d%b%Y", 
               guide = guide_axis(n.dodge = 2)) +
  my_theme
